    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-04-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-04-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="1263"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1263">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 811.741/155</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The</hi>
                    <gloss type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Secretary of State</hi>
                    </gloss>
                    <hi rend="italic">to the British Ambassador</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRSCA1"
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Spring Rice</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 749]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-04-21">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 21, 1915</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: Referring to your note of March 26, 1915,
                    with regard to the request of the Governor of British Honduras for information
                    as to whether this Government would be willing to permit the sending of
                    commercial messages by radio from that colony to addresses in the United States,
                    through New Orleans, in code, under certain restrictions, I have the honor to
                    inform you that this Government deems it inadvisable to grant the permission
                    desired by the Governor of British Honduras. The transmission of commercial code
                    messages between the United States radio stations and radio stations in foreign
                    belligerent countries has not been permitted even in the case of the Tuckerton
                    station operated under control of the Navy Department, and it is not considered
                    advisable to make an exception to this rule in the case of radio stations in
                    belligerent territory.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">W. J. Bryan</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
